STYLE BIBLE — Corsair Catch Sprite Standard

You are generating a single game sprite for a pirate-themed Pokémon-style RPG called Corsair Catch. Every sprite in this game must look like it belongs in the same world — a sun-baked, salt-crusted, magic-infused pirate sea.

RENDERING TECHNIQUE:
Hand-placed pixel art. Every shape is built from deliberate, chunky pixel clusters — minimum 2x2 pixel groupings for any detail, never single scattered pixels. No anti-aliasing. No dithering. No soft gradients. No airbrush. No painterly blending. Color transitions happen in clean, hard-edged bands — a maximum of 3-4 shades per material (shadow, base, highlight, specular). The look is closer to SNES/GBA-era sprite work than modern HD pixel art.

OUTLINE RULES:
Every sprite has a continuous, unbroken 1-pixel black (#1A1A2E) outline around its entire external silhouette. No gaps, no breaks, no fading. Interior detail lines use a dark shade of the local color (not black) — for example, dark brown (#3D2B1F) for wood grain, dark teal (#0E3B43) for ocean creatures, dark red (#5C1A1A) for fire elements. The outline is the single most important visual unifier across all sprites.

